Abstract
Dierential Evolution (DE) is one of the most popular and powerful stochastic population-
based algorithms used for solving optimization problems over the continuous search
space. Due to its eectiveness and simplicity, DE has not only gained widespread
adoption among practitioners across diverse elds but has also served as a fundamental
optimizer for numerous other intricate algorithms. As a member of the evolution-
ary algorithm family, the performance of DE is strongly inuenced by the population
diversity. Since the mechanism of producing ospring in DE relies entirely on the
dierences between the population members, this algorithm is, in fact, more sensitive
to population diversity compared to other evolutionary algorithms. Consequently, the
eective management of a diverse population is not only a critical concern but also a
potential avenue for enhancing the performance of DE.
Motivated by these fundamental observations, this thesis is dedicated to enhanc-
ing the performance of DE in dealing with the real parameter optimization problem
by eectively maintaining a diverse population. To accomplish this goal, a novel
technique called Dynamic Perturbation (DP) is developed with the ability to identify
stagnant solutions in the population and introduce random noise to perturb these so-
lutions, enabling them to escape local optimum and continue exploring the search
space. Additionally, a new variant of DE, termed S-LSHADE-DP, is also introduced,
incorporating three signicant improvements compared to the canonical DE. Firstly,
S-LSHADE-DP employs two distinct mutation strategies with dierent characteristics,
enhancing the algorithms exibility. Secondly, the control parameters are adaptively
adjusted to regulate the convergence behavior of the population. Lastly, the population
diversity of S-LSHADE-DP is improved by the integration of the DP technique.
i
Extensive experiments are conducted to evaluate the eectiveness of the proposed
methods. The numerical results reveal that the proposed algorithm S-LSHADE-DP
is highly competitive with state-of-the-art DE-based algorithms. Analyses further
conrms that the proposed techniques, despite their simplicity, successfully maintain
diversity and eectively control the convergence behavior of the population. More-
over, according to a post-analysis of a competition on real parameter single-objective
optimization organized at the 2022 IEEE Congress on Evolutionary Computation, S-
LSHADE-DP attains the second highest ranking with respect to the solution quality.
The proposed techniques in this thesis are expected to be useful tools for practitioners
when designing new algorithms in the future.
Keywords: Numerical optimization, dierential evolution, population diversity
improvement.

1.1 Motivation and scope
This thesis focuses on the black-box single objective bound-constrained optimization
problem over the continuous space. Without loss of generality, this problem can be
mathematically expressed as follows:

the eld of optimization, where techniques developed for solving this problem serve
as the foundation upon which more advanced methods, like multi-objective, multi-
modal, multi-tasking, large-scale, and constrained optimization algorithms are built.
Consequently, improvements to single-objective algorithms are signicantly important
as they have a broad impact on other sub-domains of the eld.
Among stochastic methods for solving problem (1.1), Dierential Evolution (DE)
[1] is one of the most eective algorithms, which has been applied in a wide range
of real-world complex optimization problems [2, 3, 4]. The performance of DE
and its variants has been shown to clearly outperform other popular evolutionary
1
algorithms, such as Genetic Algorithm (GA) or Particle Swarm Optimization (PSO)
[5], while the time and space complexities are much lower compared to some of
the most competitive optimizers, like the Covariance Matrix Adaptation Evolutionary
Strategy (CMA-ES) [4]. These advantages allow the algorithm to handle large-scale and
expensive problems, and thus make DE highly applicable in practice. The eectiveness
of DE has also been demonstrated through the annual prestigious competitions on real
parameter optimization, organized at the leading conferences in the eld of evolutionary
computation such as the IEEE Congress on Evolutionary Computation (IEEE CEC) and
The Genetic and Evolutionary Computation Conference (GECCO), where numerous
DE-based algorithms have been proposed and consistently achieved top rankings [6].
In addition to the outstanding performance, the simplicity, compact structure, ease of
understanding, and ease of implementation are also the key reasons that make DE a
popular algorithm and favored by practitioners from other elds [4].
Like many other evolutionary algorithms, population diversity is a critical issue in
dierential evolution. Since the mechanism of producing ospring in DE completely
depends on the deviations between population members, the performance of DE is, in
fact, even more sensitive to the population diversity than other evolutionary algorithms.
Once premature convergence and stagnation occur, the algorithm loses the capability
of exploration. The search then comes to a standstill even though the budget of function
evaluations has still not been used up.
Due to the signicant impact of population diversity on the performance of dif-
ferential evolution algorithm, this issue has attracted considerable interest in the com-
putational intelligence community, with many methods have been proposed, such as
multi-population [7, 8], niching [9, 3], etc. The multi-population techniques main-
tain the diversity by evolving multiple sub-populations (also called islands) during the
search process. One of the most common diagrams is to employ two sub-populations,
one for exploration and the other for exploitation. On the other hand, niching methods,
such as crowding [10] and tness sharing [11], are commonly used in multimodal
optimization. These methods maintain multiple niches within a single population to
preserve the diversity and prevent the population from being trapped in local optima
2
[12]. The above methods, although bringing very promising results, are relatively
complex, and thus, lose their advantage of simplicity that has made DE a very pop-
ular optimizer. This motivates us to develop a simple technique with a capability of
maintaining the population diversity to enhance the performance and the stability of
the dierential evolution.
1.2 Thesis contributions and organization
Motivated by the importance of maintaining the population diversity in dierential
evolution algorithm, this thesis is dedicated to eectively address this issue. The
contributions of the thesis are briey summarized as follows:
Dynamic Perturbation (DP) technique. This thesis proposes a simple pertur-
bation technique to improve the population diversity in which the perturbation
magnitude is adjusted dynamically during the course of the search. The proposed
DP technique is able to identify stagnation in the population. When stagnation is
detected in an individual, the perturbation is invoked to help the individual escape
from the local optimum and continue exploring the search space. This technique
is designed to be integrated into any population-based algorithms working on
the continuous space. We expect that this simple technique will further improve
the performance of existing algorithms and become useful tool for practitioners
when designing new algorithms in the future.
S-LSHADE-DP algorithm. This thesis introduces an algorithm named S-
LSHADE-DP for solving the single-objective bound-constrained optimization
problem over the continuous space. The algorithm is developed based on the
skeleton of dierential evolution algorithm, and is equipped with three additional
features as follows: 8) the proposed DP technique is applied to improve the pop-
ulation diversity; 88) instead of xing the control parameters as in the canonical
DE, a parameter adaptation mechanism called L-SHADE [13] is modied by
a deterministic rule and applied to the proposed algorithm to manipulate the
convergence behaviour of the population; and 888) instead of using a single muta-
3
tion strategy, S-LSHADE-DP is equipped with two dierent mutation strategies
with dierent characteristics, making the algorithm more stable and reducing
stagnation in the population.
Experimental study. To examine the ecacy of the proposed DP technique and
S-LSHADE-DP algorithm, extensive experiments are conducted over the latest
set of challenging benchmarks from the 2022 IEEE CEC and GECCO compe-
tition on real parameter single-objective optimization [14]. Comparisons with
the winners of the 2020 and 2021 competitions demonstrate that the proposed
algorithm is highly competitive with state-of-the-art methods. Further analyses
also show that each of the proposed methods does improve the population di-
versity and has its contribution to the overall performance of S-LSHADE-DP
algorithm. Besides, according to the results of 2022 IEEE CEC competition
and a careful post-competition analysis in [15], out of 13 contest entries, the
proposed algorithm is ranked as the second-best in terms of solution quality
and ranked as the fourth-best in terms of both solution quality and conver-
gence speed. The implementation of the proposed algorithm is available at
https://github.com/cuonglvsoict/S-LSHADE-DP.
Organization: The remaining parts of this thesis are organized as follows: Chapter 2
provides fundamental backgrounds of optimization, including an description of the
dierential evolution algorithm and its recent advances. This chapter also includes
a discussion on the inuences of population diversity on the performance of DE, as
well as existing methods for addressing this problem. Chapter 3 introduces the DP
technique for maintaining population diversity and the S-LSHADE-DP algorithm for
solvinng the problem (1.1). The experimental results on the test benchmarks of the
2022 IEEE CEC competition on real parameter optimization are provided in Chapter 4.
Finally, the chapter Conclusion concludes the thesis.

This chapter introduces the dierential evolution algorithm and the population diversity
problem. Firstly, Section 2.1 provides fundamental backgrounds of optimization and

2.1 Backgrounds
This section introduces the most basic and important concepts around an optimiza-
tion problem. The most popular methods for solving optimization problems are also
provided in brief.

of natural organisms to the most complex human economic and social activities, as
decisions are always oriented towards maximizing benets within limited resources.

2.1.2 Common techniques for solving optimization problems
The methods for solving optimization problems can be divided into two categories:
exact methods and approximate methods. With the exact approach, the algorithm
always guarantees to return a globally optimal solution. However, such methods cannot
be applied to most real-world problems due to their high computational complexities.
On the other hand, approximate optimization methods do not guarantee for the global
optimum but often provide a good enough solution within an acceptable computing
time, and thus they could be considered as eective alternatives to exact algorithms.
Below, we give a short overview of these methods.
Exact methods
In exact methods, typically all feasible candidates of the search domain are evaluated
and the best solution is chosen. Some popular methods are listed below:
Linear programming is used to maximize or minimize a linear objective function
subject to linear equality and inequality constraints. There are many method
proposed for solving a linear program like simplex method, interior point method
(polynomial-time), which are embedded in powerful commercial optimization
tools like IBM CPLEX, Gurobi, etc.
Dynamic programming is based on the recursive division of a complex problem
8
into simpler sub-problems, resulting in a sequence of partial decisions. The
approach involves storing the results of subproblems and reusing them when
needed, which reduces the time complexity of the algorithm.
Branch and bound method is based on an implicit enumeration mechanism
through all solutions using a tree structure, with the root node representing the
entire problem and its search space, and the leaf nodes representing possible
solutions. There is a method called Branch and Cut that combines the branch
and bound method with the use of cutting planes to tighten the constraints and
gradually reduce the search space. These methods are commonly used for solving
integer programs.
The above methods are often only applicable to problems with small sizes (number of
decision variables) and/or where the structures of the objective function and constraints
are explicitly dened so that dierentiation is possible. As the problem size increases,
the number of solutions needed to be evaluated increases rapidly (often exponentially).
Finding the global optimal solution for these problems is dicult, if not impossible.
Approximate methods
The approximate approach is an eective alternative and the most commonly applied
method to solve such real-world complex optimization problems. These methods can
be divided further into two types: approximation algorithms and heuristic algorithms.
Both do not guarantee to nd the global optimum, but the dierence is that heuristics
often nd a good enough solution in an acceptable time, while approximation
algorithms provide solutions with proven performance guarantees, i.e., the solution
quality and computational cost are guaranteed at a proven threshold. The remaining
parts of this thesis will focus mainly on the heuristic algorithms.
Due to the increasing demand for solving large-scale optimization problems,
heuristic algorithms have attracted attention and been widely used for about 30 years.
These algorithms include problem-specic heuristics, which are only designed to solve
specic problems, and metaheuristics, which are designed as frameworks that can be
applied to any optimization problem. The performance of heuristic algorithms is not
9
guaranteed by any theoretical proof as in approximation algorithms, and is usually
proven through experimental comparisons and statistics. Searching for an optimal
solution in heuristics relies mainly on stochastic operators and the trial-and-error
mechanism until obtaining a solution with a satisfactory quality. The search process
can be population-based, or single solution-based.
Typical examples for population-based algorithms are the class of Evolutionary
Algorithms (EAs), including Genetic Algorithm (GA) [16], Dierential Evolution
(DE) [1], Co-evolutionary Algorithm (CEA) [17], Evolutionary Strategies (ES) [18],
Evolutionary Programming (EP) [19], Genetic Programming (GP) [20], etc. Another
class includes algorithms inspired by Swarm Intelligence, such as Particle Swarm
Optimization Algorithm (PSO) [21], Ant Colony Optimization (ACO) [22], Articial
Bee Colony Algorithm (ABC) [23], Firey Algorithm (FA) [24], etc.
Most popular single solution-based algorithms are Local Search (LS) [25], Iterated
Local Search (ILS) [26], Guided Local Search (GLS) [27], Variable Neighborhood
Search (VNS) [28], Large-scale Neighborhood Search (LNS) and Very Large-scale
Neighborhood Search (VLNS) [29], Greedy Randomized Adaptive Search Procedure
(GRASP) [30], Simulated Annealing (SA) [31], Tabu Search (TS) [32], etc.
Wolpert and his colleagues pointed out in their famous No Free Lunch theorem that
there is no algorithm that performs better than any other algorithm [33]. Each algorithm
has its own advantages suitable for a specic type of problem. If algorithm A is more
ecient than algorithm B in solving a certain problem, there will be another problem in
which using algorithm B will yield higher eciency than A. In addition, there is always
a trade-o between solution quality and computation cost in heuristic algorithms, i.e.,
the desire for higher solution quality requires a larger number of evaluations.

2.2.1 Canonical dierential evolution
Since the rst introduction by Storn and Price [1], dierential evolution has served
as one of the foremost algorithms in numerical optimization. Being a member of
evolutionary algorithm family, DE also seeks the optimal solution by evolving its
population. A canonical DE algorithm involves four key steps, including population
initialization, dierential mutation, crossover, and survival selection (as illustrated in
Figure 2.3). Only the last three steps are repeated in subsequent iterations until one
of halting conditions is reached. In each generation, a donor vector is created for

IMODE
Improved Multi-Operator Dierential Evolution (IMODE) [35] is the winner of the

of individuals evolved by each mutation strategy is calculated based on the population
diversity and quality of solutions. A local search procedure called Sequential Quadratic

frequently been used as a baseline algorithm recently.
APGSK
IMODE
In the 2021 IEEE CEC competition, an algorithm called APGSK IMODE [36] which is
the hybridization of the Gaining-Sharing Knowledge-Based Algorithm (GSK) [42] and
IMODE was proposed and demonstrated impressive performance. APGSK IMODE
took advantages of both IMODE and GSK by constantly updating the probabilities of
performing these algorithms based on their yielded solutions quality. The algorithm
provided a stable convergence to the global optima in most non-shifted test problems
(i.e., the objective function is not shifted) and won the competition for the non-shifted
cases.
17
NL-SHADE-RSP
While APGSK IMODE demonstrated its superiority in non-shifted test instances, an-
other algorithm called NL-SHADE-RSP [37] won the 2021 CEC competition for the
shifted problems (i.e., the objective function is shifted). The NL-SHADE-RSP algo-
rithm is an improved version of SHADE which employed the non-linear population size
reduction method and the rank-based selective pressure mechanism to boost the perfor-
mance of mutation. However, NL-SHADE-RSP havs worse performance compared to
IMODE when the best known solution is located close to the axis origin.
2.3 Population diversity in dierential evolution
In dierential evolution algorithm or evolutionary algorithms in general, population
diversity is a critical factor to achieve good performance. This section presents how
the population diversity eects the search behaviour of DE. The existing methods for
population diversity management are also introduced.
2.3.1 Inuences of population diversity on the search performance
In population genetics and evolutionary biology, population diversity refers to the
amount of genetic variation that exists within the population [43], which is an important
factor in determining the evolutionary potential and adaptive capacity of a population.
The diversity can be measured by the number of dierent alleles at a particular gene
locus, the frequency of those alleles in the population, or the proportion of individuals
in the population that carry two dierent alleles at a particular gene locus. High genetic
diversity suggests that the population has a large pool of genetic variation to draw from,
which can help it adapt to changing environmental conditions or resist disease and other
threats. In contrast, low genetic diversity can make the population more vulnerable to
environmental changes, diseases, and other threats, as it may lack the genetic variation
needed to adapt and survive.
In the context of evolutionary algorithms, population diversity refers to the degree
to which the solutions in the population dier from each other. This is a critical
18
concept as it determines the algorithms ability to explore the search space eectively
and nd high-quality solutions. Maintaining a diverse population during the search
process enables the algorithm to explore a broader range of the solutions space and
nd new peaks, while preventing from being trapped in local optima. When population
diversity is lost, the population becomes genetically homogeneous, meaning that the
individuals within the population are similar to one another. Since the strength of
evolutionary algorithms lies in the cooperation between individuals and the global
view of the population, a population-based algorithm without population diversity
becomes a single-solution-based algorithm, and the above advantages no longer exist.
Like other evolutionary algorithms, the performance of DE is closely related
to the population diversity. However, DE is even more sensitive to this factor than
other algorithms since its mechanism of generating ospring depends wholly on the
variations (or dierences) between individuals. In particular, new genetic materials in
DE are only created in the dierential mutation step by subtracting individuals, like
x
r
1
x
r
2
or x
best
x
i
(see section 2.2). It should be noted that the crossover creates
the trial solution u

by simply mixing the mutant vector v
8

parent x
8
, without generating any genetic materials. When population diversity is lost,
the dierences between population members vanish. The algorithm then behaves as
trying all combinations of current solutions components, which is similar to discrete
optimization. The evolution is thus disrupted quickly and the population falls into
stagnation at a point that may not be the global optimum. This phenomenon is known
as premature convergence, which prevents the algorithm from nding better solutions
even though there is still available computational budget. This is a serious problem that
signicantly degrades the performance of the algorithm.
2.3.2 Existing approaches for population diversity improvement
Since the population diversity is a crucial issue that inuences the search performance
of an evolutionary algorithm, there has been signicant attention and eort dedicated to
enhance the population diversity. Numerous techniques have been proposed to address
this issue, with some being applicable to any evolutionary algorithm, while others are
19
specically designed for dierential evolution algorithm. This section provides a brief
overview of some prominent techniques.
Reinitialization
Reinitialization [44, 45, 46, 47] refers to the process of regenerating and replacing
some or all of the individuals in the current population with new randomly generated
individuals. This can help to introduce new genetic diversity into the population, and
potentially improve the search process by exploring dierent regions of the solution
space that may not have been previously explored. Reinitialization is simple and can
be applied to any optimization problems and algorithms for maintaining diversity and
promoting exploration. However, it also has some potential drawbacks, including
loss of good solutions, increased computational cost, randomness and unpredictability,
trade-o between exploration and exploitation, and problem-dependent eectiveness.
Multi-population
The multi-population technique [7, 48, 49, 50] involves maintaining multiple popula-
tions (also called islands) of candidate solutions simultaneously during the optimization
process, where each population evolves independently in order to enhance the explo-
ration of the search space and diversify the solution. One of the most common diagrams
is to employ two sub-populations, one for exploration and the other for exploitation.
By maintaining multiple populations, the algorithm can explore dierent regions of the
search space simultaneously, thereby increasing the chances of nding high-quality so-
lutions. However, it may also introduce additional challenges, such as implementation
complexity, coordination among populations and selection of migration or exchange
strategies between populations.
Ensemble of multiple search operators
An ensemble of search operators [35, 36, 51] involves combining or using in parallel
dierent search operators that generate new candidate solutions during optimization. By
combining dierent search operators with dierent search behaviours, the algorithm can
collectively cover a wider range of the solution space, leading to increased diversity in
20
the population. Moreover, dierent search behaviours result in dierent neighborhood
structures of the operators, which helps the population to explore dierent regions of
the solution space more eectively and prevents it from stagnation at local optima.
One approach that has been eectively used with the ensemble of search operators is
the integration with the multi-population technique. For instance, a multi-population
approach can be used where two sub-populations are maintained, one utilizing an
exploration operator and the other utilizing an exploitation operator. The exploitation
population can see the exploration population, but not vice versa, resulting in a
balanced equilibrium between exploration and exploitation. This integration allows
for leveraging the strengths of dierent search operators in separate sub-populations,
leading to a synergistic eect and potentially enhancing the overall search performance
of the algorithm.
Niching
Niching techniques [52, 53, 54] are used to address the issue of premature conver-
gence by promoting diversity within the population and allowing the the algorithms to
maintain multiple solutions in dierent niches of the search space. These techniques
are commonly used in multi-modal optimization problems, where the goal is to nd
all the extremum of the search space. Niching typically involves mechanisms that
encourage individuals in the population to spread out across the search space, maintain
diversity, and explore dierent regions. Some common niching techniques include t-
ness sharing, crowding, clustering, and speciation. Fitness sharing involves assigning
lower tness values to individuals in crowded regions of the search space, promoting
diversity. Crowding involves selecting individuals based on their proximity to each
other in the search space, favoring solutions that are farther apart. Speciation involves
maintaining separate subpopulations within the main population, where individuals
in dierent subpopulations are prevented from mating or competing with each other,
promoting diversity. By maintaining diversity and exploring dierent regions, niching
techniques can help evolutionary algorithms to avoid premature convergence and dis-
cover multiple solutions, providing a more comprehensive and diverse set of solutions
to the optimization problem.
21
Parameter adaptation
The inuences of control parameters on the population diversity have been well-studied.
In the context of dierential evolution algorithm, these parameters include the scaling
factor , the crossover rate ', and the population size #. Theoretical analyses
have been conducted to understand the relationships between these parameters and the
population variance [38, 39, 40, 41]. The observations can be summarized as follows.
Scaling factor : The scaling factor in DE determines the magnitude of the
perturbation applied to the dierence vectors during the mutation operation.
While a larger scaling factor allows for larger perturbations and more aggressive
exploration of the search space, a smaller scaling factor, on the other hand, leads
to smaller perturbations and more conservative exploration.
Crossover rate ': The crossover rate in DE determines the probability of
recombination between the mutant vector v
8
and the parent vector x
8
during the
crossover operation as given in (2.8). A higher crossover rate promotes more
recombination, leading to increased exploration and diversity, while a lower
crossover rate promotes more exploitation, leading to convergence towards local
optima.
Population size #: A larger population size generally increases the diversity of
the population, as it allows for more exploration of the search space and provides
a larger pool of potential solutions. However, a very large population size may
lead to higher computational costs and slower convergence. On the other hand,
a smaller population size may result in a faster convergence, but it may reduce
the diversity of the population and result in premature convergence to suboptimal
solutions.
Due to the signicant eects of these parameters on population diversity, and the fact
that their optimal values are problem-dependent, extensive eorts have been conducted
to dynamically adapt these parameters during the search process. Numerous adaptive
DE algorithms, such as jDe [40], JADE [55], SHADE [34, 13], EPSDE [56], jSO
[50], etc., have been proposed and demonstrated their eectiveness in maintaining the
22
population diversity. More comprehensive surveys can be found in [3, 4].
Historical archive
Historical memory, also known as external archive [55, 57, 58], refers to the storage
and utilization of past information during the optimization process. Historical memory
helps in preserving diversity in the population as it allows the algorithm to remember
previously explored solutions and prevents them from being lost or forgotten during
the optimization process. By storing information about previously visited regions of
the search space, the algorithm can remember promising solutions that were explored
but not selected in previous iterations. This information can guide the algorithm
to revisit those regions and explore further, potentially leading to the discovery of
better solutions and escaping from local optima. However, historical memory requires
additional storage and computational overhead, and may not always guarantee improved
the performance.

3.2 Proposed DE-based algorithm
This section introduces the algorithm named S-LSHADE-DP. This algorithm is devel-
oped based on the skeleton of the dierential evolution algorithm, in which, the main
ow of the algorithm is kept as in Figure 2.3. Specically, the algorithm starts by
randomly generating a population of # individuals. In each generation, mutation and
crossover are performed to produce new solutions. These ospring are evaluated re-
garding to the objective function and directly compared to their corresponding parents.
Better solutions in the comparisons are then selected to form the population of the next
generation. However, compared to the canonical DE (Subsection 2.2.1), the proposed
algorithm S-LSHADE-DP has three additional features as follows:
Dierential mutation: S-LSHADE-DP employs two dierent strategies with
dierent characteristics that are suitable for dierent types of problems. This
makes the algorithm more exible and reduces the likelihood of being trapped in
28
local optimum.
Parameter adaptation: The L-SHADE adaptation method [13] is adopted with
a modication in the setting of crossover rate ' to manipulate the convergence
behavior of the population.
Integration with the dynamic perturbation: The proposed dynamic perturba-
tion method is applied after every generation to enhance the population diversity.
The detailed descriptions of above features are presented in the next three subsections.
After that, the nal subsection provides the computational complexity of the proposed
algorithm.
3.2.1 Dierential mutation
Instead of using a single mutation strategy as in the canonical DE, we utilize two
dierent mutation strategies in S-LSHADE-DP. The rationales behind are as follows:
Firstly, as we have already mentioned the No Free Lunch theorem [33] in Sec-
tion 2.1 of Chapter 2, there is no one-size-ts-all optimization algorithm that
performs the best for all types of problems. In other words, there is no universal
method that outperforms all others on all possible optimization problems. This
theorem implies that the eectiveness of a method is problem-dependent. There-
fore, it is dicult, if not impossible, to select a single versatile mutation strategy
that works eectively for all types of problems in real-world scenarios.
Secondly, although we do not know the characteristics of a specic real-world
optimization problem that the algorithm will encounter, we do know one thing
for sure that, from the perspective of modality, optimization problems can be
divided into two types, unimodal problems with single extremum and multimodal
problems with multiple peaks [59].
Based on above observations, two dierent mutation strategies with dierent charac-
teristics are employed in S-LSHADE-DP, each with its own strengths that are suitable
for specic types of problems and can complement the other. These mutation strategies
are described below:

4.4 Sensitivity analysis
In this subsection, a sensitivity analysis is conducted to assess the contribution of each
component to the overall performance of S-LSHADE-DP. The experiment includes the
proposed algorithm S-LSHADE-DP and its four variants as follows:
1) S-LSHADE: S-LSHADE-DP without using the dynamic perturbation technique.
2) S-LSHADE-DP/target/1: S-LSHADE-DP using only one mutation strategy,
that is, DE/target/1.
3) S-LSHADE-DP/cpb/1: S-LSHADE-DP using only the DE/current-to-pbest/1
mutation strategy.
4) LSHADE-DP: S-LSHADE-DP using L-SHADE adaptation without the modi-
cation in the setting of '.
The mean and standard deviation of error values achieved by S-LSHADE-DP and above
variants on the D20 test problems are reported in Table 4.5. The results of Wilcoxons
rank-sum test and Friedman test are also summarized in the last two rows of the table,
where +, =, and - indicate that the S-LSHADE-DP algorithm is statistically
better than, worse than, and equivalent to the corresponding variant, respectively. It
42
can be seen that S-LSHADE-DP is the best performing version with the lowest ranking
compared to other variants. As shown in Table 4.5, S-LSHADE-DP is statistically better
than S-LSHADE in four problems (two basic functions f4 and f5, hybrid function f8,
and composition function f12), better than LSHADE-DP in six problems (two basic
functions f2 and f4, hybrid function f6, and three composition functions f10 - f12), and
equal to these variants in the remaining problems. These results conrm the signicant
eciency of the dynamic perturbation technique and the modication in the setting
of ' of L-SHADE. Compared to S-LSHADE-DP/cpb/1, the additional use of the
DE/target/1 strategy helps S-LSHADE-DP win in two problems (hybrid function f6
and composition function f11), but lose in two other problems (two hybrid functions
f7 and f8). Finally, the results of S-LSHADE-DP/target/1 show that the absence of
information from best solutions degrades the performance of S-LSHADE-DP in most
basic functions and hybrid functions. However, the bright spot is that S-LSHADE-
DP/target/1 provides a stable convergence to the global optima of the basic function f2
and composition functions f11, derives the best solution in composition functions f9,
all of which can not be achieved by other variants, even three state-of-the-art algorithms
used in the previous experiment. Up to this point, we can conclude that the overall
performance of S-LSHADE-DP is not solely attributable to a single component, but
rather the combination of all of them.

Since, in an evolutionary algorithm, population members often converge towards the
best solution, a higher value of " indicates that the population is more diverse.
We consider the " value obtained by the proposed algorithm S-LSHADE-DP
and its variant S-LSHADE which does not employ the dynamic perturbation method.
The normalized " values during the evolution process of several test problems are
plotted in Figure 4.3, showing two interesting points as follows. The rst one is the
dierence in population diversity of the S-LSHADE algorithm (red dashed lines) in
dierent search stages. Specically, during the rst half of the search process, S-
LSHADE maintains high " values, indicating high population diversity. It can be
seen that the red lines are almost at during this stage. Immediately after that, the
deviation decreases rapidly in all cases, suggesting that the populations have crowded
in small regions around the best solutions. This phenomenon can only be explained by
the setting of the crossover rate ', as given in Eq. (3.8), that is, zero-' in the rst
half and random-' in the later half.
The second point is that, rapid convergence in the later stage of S-LSHADE is likely
44
to lead to premature convergence and stagnation, and that is where the perturbation
technique comes in handy. Figure 4.3 shows a signicant dierence in population
diversity between S-LSHADE-DP and S-LSHADE. In the early stage, the gap between
the two algorithms is relatively small since the population diversity is still high in S-
LSHADE. As time passes, the gap increases due to the perturbation techniques eect.
By incorporating the setting of ' and the perturbation technique, S-LSHADE-DP
can slowly improve solutions in the rst half of the search to preserve diversity and
exploration ability, speed up convergence in the second half to rapidly exploit explored
good regions, while maintaining a diverse population throughout the entire search
process.

which prevents the algorithm from sub-optimal solutions, while fast convergence could
result in losing of diversity and degrade the performance at the end.

Conclusion
This thesis focuses on enhancing the performance of the dierential evolution algo-
rithm in dealing with numerical optimization problems. The central idea is to eectively
manage the population diversity throughout the evolution process, thus preventing the
population from premature convergence. To achieve this goal, a simple technique
called dynamic perturbation was proposed to eectively improve the population di-
versity during the evolution process. Additionally, a novel DE-based algorithm called
S-LSHADE-DP was also developed integrating with the proposed DP technique. Ex-
tensive experiments were conducted on the test suite of the CEC22 competition on
real parameter single-objective bound-constrained optimization. The numerical results
demonstrated the superior performance of the proposed algorithm S-LSHADE-DP
across numerous test problems when compared to state-of-the-art algorithms. Sensitiv-
ity analysis also demonstrated that the dynamic perturbation technique does successfully
help improving the population diversity and enhancing the algorithms performance.
To further validate the eectiveness of the proposed techniques, future research
can explore their integration with other algorithms and analyze the resulting outcomes.
Additionally, although the results have been encouraging, it is important to conduct
more evaluations on real-world optimization problems to thoroughly validate the prac-
tical applicability and stability of the proposed techniques.
